HEADWORD: Lithotome
<hw>Lith"o*tome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ cutting
stones; <grk>li`qos</grk> stone + <?/ to cut: cf. F.
<ets>lithotome</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A stone so formed by
nature as to appear as if cut by art.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An instrument used for cutting
the bladder in operations for the stone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lithotomical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Lithotomic</ent>⟦br⟧
